7 So bitter is it, that death is hardly more so;
8 but to treat of the good that I found there,
9 I will tell of the other things that I perceived there.

31 And behold, almost at the beginning of the steep ascent,
32 a she-leopard, light and very swift,
33 covered with a spotted pelt;

55 And just as one who eagerly acquires,
56 and the time comes that makes him lose it,
57 weeps and grieves in all his thoughts;

88 See the beast because of which I turned back;
89 help me against her, famous sage,
90 for she makes my veins and pulses tremble.”

91 “You must take another journey,”
92 he replied, after he saw me weeping,
93 “if you wish to escape from this savage place;

94 for this beast, because of which you cry out,
95 does not let anyone pass along her path,
96 but hinders him so much that she kills him;

112 Therefore, for your own good, I think and discern
113 that you should follow me, and I will be your guide,
114 and I will lead you from here through an eternal place;

115 where you will hear the desperate shrieks,
116 you will see the ancient sorrowful spirits,
117 each of whom cries out for the second death;

121 If you should wish to ascend to those afterwards,
122 there will be a soul more worthy than I for that:
123 I will leave you with her when I depart;

127 He rules everywhere and reigns there;
128 there is his city and his lofty throne:
129 oh happy he whom he chooses there!”
